# Rule 1 — Velocity over compatibility

This project optimizes for **speed of delivery**. Treat this as the top constraint in every change.

## Non-negotiables

- **No legacy methods**: Do not introduce, preserve, or recommend deprecated APIs, compatibility shims, dual code paths, or “we support both old and new” patterns unless the user explicitly asks for backward compatibility.
- **Breaking changes are allowed**: Prefer clean, modern interfaces. Remove obsolete entry points, flags, and indirection instead of layering adapters to keep old behavior alive.
- **Delete over wrap**: When replacing behavior, remove the old implementation rather than keeping it “just in case.”
- **No quality shortcuts**: Velocity is not an excuse to bypass quality checks (e.g. disabling eslint rules, suppressing lint/type errors, or similar cheats) to force a change through.

## For the agent

- Default to the **current** canonical approach for the stack (framework APIs, module layout, config shape).
- If a choice is “safe for old callers” vs “simpler for new code,” choose **simpler for new code** unless told otherwise.
- Do not block refactors with hypothetical external consumers; this repo accepts breakage.
- Treat “velocity” as permission for clean breaking changes, not permission to weaken guardrails.
- For UI polish tasks, prefer low-effort reuse of existing patterns (especially mobile-first layouts) and avoid broad desktop redesigns unless explicitly requested.
